descript.purpose: The Solar and Wind Energy Resource Assessment (SWERA) Geospatial Toolkit (GsT) is a map-based software application that can be used for decision making and policy analysis in addition to planning for future energy projects. The SWERA application utilizes Geographical Information Systems (GIS) to develop common scenarios to evaluate potential locations for solar or wind energy plants.

procstep.procdesc:
Abstract or brief narrative description containing detailed information (Abstract): Geographic Information Systems (GIS) data intended for use in the Geospatial toolkit or with any GIS software.
Purpose for developing the Product including any objectives and concerns (Purpose): The Solar and Wind Energy Resource Assessment (SWERA) Geospatial Toolkit (GsT) is a map-based software application that can be used for decision making and policy analysis in addition to planning for future energy projects. The SWERA application utilizes Geographical Information Systems (GIS) to develop common scenarios to evaluate potential locations for solar or wind energy plants.
Additional information describing the Product content (Supplemental Information): The zip file contains the available geospatial toolkit data and metadata. Each country's data package depends on the data provided by the SWERA partners.
The shapefile was downloaded from the following SWERA website: http://swera.unep.net/index.php?id=7 The data was then reprojected into GCS_WGS_1984 by GIST. The Solar and Wind Energy Resource Assessment (SWERA) started in 2001 as a US$ 9.1 million pilot project, co-financed with US$ 6.8 million from the Global Environment Facility (GEF). It was managed by the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and more specifically by its Division of Technology, Industry and Economics (DTIE) in collaboration with more than 25 partners around the world. With the success of the project in 13 pilot countries: Bangladesh, Brazil, China, Cuba, El Salvador, Ethiopia, Ghana, Guatemala, Honduras, Kenya, Nepal, Nicaragua, and Sri Lanka, SWERA has expanded in 2006 into a full programme. Its mission is to provide high quality information in suitable formats on renewable energy resources for countries and regions around the world, along with the tools needed to apply these data in ways that facilitate renewable energy policies and investments. In 2006 NASA agreed to fund a US$ 1 million 3-year project to continue the evolution of SWERA into a distributed and global decision support system and to prototype complementary small hydro power assessments utlizing NASA Earth-Science research results. It is recognized that the various data and tool providers will continue to independently meet their individual missions. However through well defined specifications and interfaces buiding on the SWERA database, all partners and their clients will benefit. The premise of SWERA is that precise and reliable information on renewable energy potential, though having a low commercial value, is an absolute prerequisite for encouraging policies and investments in the sector. Such information allows a better identification of potential projects and a better informed decision-making, hence reducing project planning time, as well as investor risk.
